problem:
Expand and simplify completely: \begin{align*}
x\left(x(1+x)+2x\right)-3(x^2-x+2)
\end{align*}

partial_solution:
I need to apply the distributive property of multiplication over addition to expand the expression inside the parentheses, and then combine any like terms.

First, I distribute x over the terms in the innermost parentheses: \begin{align*}
x\left(x(1+x)+2x\right) &= x\left(x+x^2+2x\right)\\
&= x\cdot x+x\cdot x^2+x\cdot 2x\\
&= x^2+x^3+2x^2
\end{align*}

Then, I distribute -3 over the terms in the other parentheses: \begin{align*}
-3(x^2-x+2) &= -3\cdot x^2-3\cdot (-x)-3\cdot 2\\
&= -3x^2+3x-6
\end{align*}

ground_truth_solution:
Begin by distributing in the innermost parentheses: \begin{align*}
&\ \ \ \ x\left(x(1+x)+2x\right)-3(x^2-x+2) \\&= x(x+x^2+2x) - 3(x^2-x+2)
\end{align*} Now, distribute again: \begin{align*}
x^2+x^3+2x^2-3x^2+3x-6
\end{align*} Finally, combine like terms to get \begin{align*}
\boxed{x^3+3x-6}
\end{align*}

correct_last_step:
Next, I remove the parentheses and combine the two expressions: \begin{align*}
x^2+x^3+2x^2-3x^2+3x-6
\end{align*}

